    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-06-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-06-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="587"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d587">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">560.M2/354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 214 (C. 67)</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-14">June 14,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honour, under instructions from His
                    Majesty’s Principal Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, to inform you that
                    His Majesty’s Government in the United Kingdom have had under consideration the
                    question of their continued adherence to the Convention for the Abolition of
                    Import and Export Prohibitions and Restrictions which was signed at Geneva on
                    the 8th November, 1927, with special regard to the impending consideration of
                    the whole question of import restrictions quotas and similar measures by the
                    Monetary and Economic Conference.<note n="2" xml:id="d587fn2">For correspondence
                        relating to the Monetary and Economic Conference held in London, June
                        12–July 27, see <ref target="#pg_452">pp. 452</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. His Majesty’s Government have deemed it advisable to avail themselves of their
                    right under Article 6 of the Protocol signed at Paris on the 21st [<hi
                        rend="italic">20th</hi>] December, 1929,<note n="3" xml:id="d587fn3">For
                        text, see <ref target="frus1929v01#pg_424">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 424</ref>.</note> to be relieved of the
                    obligations accepted by them in accordance with the Convention as from the 30th
                    June, in order that they may be free to enter into any agreements bearing upon
                    the question of prohibitions, quotas and similar restrictions which may ensue
                    from the Monetary and Economic Conference. A formal declaration of withdrawal,
                    as provided for in Article 6 of the above-mentioned Protocol, has accordingly
                    been forwarded to the Secretary General of the League of Nations.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d587fn4">Sir James Eric Drummond.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Lindsay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
